{"questionId":"9714","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The following diagram shows part of the graph of&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"f(x) = \\left( {6 - 3x} \\right)\\left( {4 + x} \\right)\">\n  <mi>f</mi>\n  <mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo>\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>6</mn>\n      <mo>−</mo>\n      <mn>3</mn>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>4</mn>\n      <mo>+</mo>\n      <mi>x</mi>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>,&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x \\in \\mathbb{R}\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n  <mo>∈</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>. The shaded region <em>R</em> is bounded by the <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"x\">\n  <mi>x</mi>\n</math></span>-axis, <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"y\">\n  <mi>y</mi>\n</math></span>-axis and the graph of <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"f\">\n  <mi>f</mi>\n</math></span>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/0469ca3ea9f6e13a4e501ca8c6df22820416c329.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the area of region <em>R</em>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>28 &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9714","referenceCode":"SPM.1.SL.TZ0.10b","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Find the area of region R.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.5—Integration introduction, areas between c